<h2>Anxiety Attacks vs Panic Attacks: What's the Difference?</h2>
<p>"Anxiety attack" is not a clinical term — it's a colloquial description for episodes of intense anxiety that may or may not meet criteria for a panic attack. Understanding the distinction matters for treatment.</p>

<p><strong>Panic attacks</strong> are discrete episodes with a sudden, intense peak — typically reaching maximum intensity within minutes — and specific physical symptoms: racing heart, shortness of breath, chest tightness, dizziness, sweating, shaking, nausea, numbness, derealization. They feel catastrophic and life-threatening even when they're not.</p>

<p><strong>Anxiety attacks</strong> (in common usage) often describe episodes that are intense but more gradual in onset, with more cognitive symptoms (overwhelming worry, racing thoughts, feeling unable to cope) and less sudden physiological intensity. They may be triggered by specific stressors or seem to come from nowhere.</p>

<p>Both are treatable. The approaches overlap significantly.</p>

<h2>The Physiology of Intense Anxiety</h2>
<p>Both panic attacks and severe anxiety episodes involve the fight-or-flight response — the sympathetic nervous system's emergency mobilisation. Adrenaline surges, heart rate increases, breathing changes, muscles prepare for action. This response is adaptive for genuine physical threats. It's distressing and self-amplifying when it occurs in the absence of actual danger.</p>

<p>The catastrophic interpretation of these physical symptoms ("I'm having a heart attack," "I'm losing control," "I'll faint") is often what transforms manageable anxiety into a full attack. Understanding this mechanism is therapeutic in itself.</p>

<h2>Evidence-Based Treatment</h2>

<h3>CBT and Psychoeducation</h3>
<p>The foundation of treatment is accurate understanding. When people understand what an anxiety attack actually is — a false alarm, not a medical emergency — and how their catastrophic interpretations amplify it, the attacks become less frightening. Less frightening means less escalation, which means the attacks become less intense.</p>

<h3>Breathing and Physiological Regulation</h3>
<p>Slow, diaphragmatic breathing (4–6 breaths per minute) activates the parasympathetic nervous system and counteracts the physiological arousal of an anxiety or panic attack. This is not a long-term treatment on its own, but a useful acute management tool.</p>

<h3>Interoceptive Exposure</h3>
<p>For panic disorder specifically, interoceptive exposure — deliberately inducing the physical sensations of anxiety (through exercise, spinning, breathing through a straw) in a controlled way — is the most effective technique. It teaches the nervous system that these sensations are not dangerous, and the fear response extinguishes.</p>

<h3>Situational Exposure</h3>
<p>If anxiety attacks have led to avoidance of specific situations, graduated exposure to those situations (shopping centres, driving, public transport) is essential. Avoidance maintains the anxiety disorder; exposure resolves it.</p>

<h3>ACT for Anxiety</h3>
<p>Acceptance and Commitment Therapy approaches anxiety differently — not trying to reduce it but developing the willingness to experience anxiety while continuing to live in line with values. This reduces the struggle with anxiety, which paradoxically reduces its intensity and impact.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>What do I do during an anxiety attack?</strong><br/>
The most effective acute approach is the opposite of fighting the attack. Let it happen, observe it without catastrophising, slow your breathing, and remind yourself it will pass. Fighting an anxiety attack by trying to control or escape it amplifies it. Paradoxically, allowing it reduces its intensity and duration.</p>

<p><strong>Can anxiety attacks cause physical harm?</strong><br/>
No. Anxiety attacks feel physically dangerous but don't produce the harm they simulate. The heart doesn't fail; people don't lose consciousness from hyperventilation. This knowledge helps reduce the catastrophic interpretation that fuels escalation.</p>

<p><strong>Do I need medication as well as therapy?</strong><br/>
Not always. For many people, CBT or ACT produces complete remission without medication. For severe or frequent attacks, or where anxiety significantly impairs functioning, a combination with medication (typically SSRIs or buspirone) produces faster and more complete response.</p>

